{"id":"PELD_Cr.v2-draft","gdl_version":"2.0","concept":"gt0001","language":{"original_language":"ISO_639-1::en"},"description":{"original_author":{"name":"Anna Axell","email":"annaaxell@gmail.com"},"lifecycle_state":"Not set","details":{"en":{"id":"en","purpose":"This score can be used to assign priority to liver transplant candidates younger than 12 years old. It is an update to the prior PELD score and was adopted by OPTN in July 2023.","use":"Similar to the MELD score, but for pediatrics: determines prognosis and prioritizes receipt of liver transplantation.\nShould be used in pediatric patients under age 12 for risk stratification and transplant prioritization. \nPELD Cr was adopted as the new standard for liver transplantation priority by the Organ Procurement and Transplantation Network (OPTN) in the United States in July 2023.\nPELD Cr includes creatinine for better risk stratification. \nThe previous version of PELD was thought to underestimate mortality by as much as 17% and up to 66% of transplant candidates were listed with a medical exception (due to inadequacy of the prior formula in capturing medical severity).\nThe PELD Cr score includes creatinine to capture the degree of renal dysfunction, which is an independent predictor of 90-day mortality for pediatric candidates on the transplant list. \nThis score also updates growth failure from a categorical to continuous variable and adjustment factor for age.","misuse":"Not to be used for ages >11 years old","keywords":[]}},"other_details":{"references":"Hsu E, Schladt DP, Wey A, Perito ER, Israni AK. Improving the predictive ability of the pediatric end-stage liver disease score for young children awaiting liver transplant. Am J Transplant. 2021;21(1):222-228. doi:10.1111/ajt.15925\nThalji L, Thalji NM, Heimbach JK, et al. Renal Function Parameters and Serum Sodium Enhance Prediction of Wait-List Outcomes in Pediatric Liver Transplantation. Hepatology. 2021;73(3):1117-1131. doi:10.1002/hep.31397"},"other_